              <div class="border-b border-gray-200 pb-4 mb-6">
                <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-800">Question 7 (5 marks)</h3>
                <p class="text-gray-700 mt-2 font-medium">
                  A software development team is choosing between Agile and Waterfall methodologies for a new mobile banking application. The client requirements are well-defined but security regulations may change during development. Justify which methodology would be most appropriate and explain your reasoning.
                </p>
              </div>
              
              <div class="mb-4">
                <div class="border-l-4 border-gray-300 pl-4">
                  <div class="space-y-2">
                    <div class="border-b border-gray-300 h-6"></div>
                    <div class="border-b border-gray-300 h-6"></div>
                    <div class="border-b border-gray-300 h-6"></div>
                    <div class="border-b border-gray-300 h-6"></div>
                    <div class="border-b border-gray-300 h-6"></div>
                    <div class="border-b border-gray-300 h-6"></div>
                    <div class="border-b border-gray-300 h-6"></div>
                    <div class="border-b border-gray-300 h-6"></div>
                    <div class="border-b border-gray-300 h-6"></div>
                    <div class="border-b border-gray-300 h-6"></div>
                    <div class="border-b border-gray-300 h-6"></div>
                    <div class="border-b border-gray-300 h-6"></div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <details class="mt-6">
                <summary class="cursor-pointer bg-green-50 p-3 rounded text-green-800 font-medium hover:bg-green-100">
                  ðŸ“‹ View Marking Criteria & Sample Answer
                </summary>
                <div class="mt-4 p-4 bg-gray-50 rounded">
                  <div class="mb-4">
                    <h4 class="font-bold text-green-700 mb-2">Marking Criteria:</h4>
                    <ul class="text-sm space-y-1">
                      <li><strong>5 marks:</strong> Clearly justifies methodology choice with specific reasoning related to the scenario (changing regulations, well-defined requirements, banking context) and explains the decision rationale</li>
                      <li><strong>4 marks:</strong> Justifies methodology choice with good reasoning but may miss some scenario-specific considerations</li>
                      <li><strong>3 marks:</strong> Makes reasonable methodology choice with basic justification but lacks depth or scenario analysis</li>
                      <li><strong>2 marks:</strong> Shows understanding of methodology differences but justification is weak or not well-connected to the scenario</li>
                      <li><strong>1 mark:</strong> Demonstrates basic knowledge of methodologies but fails to provide adequate justification for the specific scenario</li>
                    </ul>
                  </div>
                  <div>
                    <h4 class="font-bold text-green-700 mb-2">Sample Answer:</h4>
                    <div class="text-sm bg-white p-3 rounded border">
                      <p><strong>Choice: Agile methodology would be most appropriate.</strong></p>
                      <p><strong>Justification:</strong> While the client requirements are well-defined, the key factor is that security regulations may change during development. Agile's iterative approach allows the team to incorporate new security requirements at the start of each sprint without requiring a complete project restart. The regular sprint reviews enable continuous validation that security requirements are being met and allow for quick adjustments if regulations change. Additionally, for a mobile banking application, user experience is critical, and Agile's emphasis on working software and user feedback will help ensure the application meets both security requirements and usability standards. The financial sector's rapid regulatory changes make Agile's flexibility essential, as Waterfall's rigid structure would require costly rework if security regulations change mid-project.</p>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </details>
            </div>

